Queries

agreements

Description

ÐŸÐ¾Ð»ÑƒÑ‡ÐµÐ½Ð¸Ðµ ÑÐ¿Ð¸ÑÐºÐ° ÑÐ¾Ð³Ð»Ð°ÑˆÐµÐ½Ð¸Ð¹ Ñ Ñ„Ð¸Ð»ÑŒÑ‚Ñ€Ð°Ñ†Ð¸ÐµÐ¹ Ð¸ Ð¿Ð°Ð³Ð¸Ð½Ð°Ñ†Ð¸ÐµÐ¹

Response

Returns a PaginatedAgreementsPaginationResult!

Arguments
Name Description
filter - AgreementFilter
options - PaginationInput

Example

Query
query agreements(
  $filter: AgreementFilter,
  $options: PaginationInput
) {
  agreements(
    filter: $filter,
    options: $options
  ) {
    currentPage
    items {
      ...AgreementFragment
    }
    totalCount
    totalPages
  }
}
Variables
{
  "filter": AgreementFilter,
  "options": PaginationInput
}
Response
{
  "data": {
    "agreements": {
      "currentPage": 987,
      "items": [Agreement],
      "totalCount": 987,
      "totalPages": 123
    }
  }
}

Query
query capitalCommit($data: GetCapitalCommitByHashInput!) {
  capitalCommit(data: $data) {
    _created_at
    _id

    status
    username
  }

Types

ID

Description

The ID scalar type represents a unique identifier, often used to refetch an object or as key for a cache. The ID type appears in a JSON response as a String; however, it is not intended to be human-readable. When expected as an input type, any string (such as "4") or integer (such as 4) input value will be accepted as an ID.

Example
"4"
